@leahrowanbooks knew IUDs were among the most effective birth control, but she never wanted one for herself—that is, until she had her first child. After her midwife cautioned that some patients showed up for their six-week post-natal checkups to find they were pregnant again, Rowan scheduled her IUD insertion that very day. She expected a cakewalk compared to her emergency C-section.
The reality, however, proved otherwise. Her experience woke her up to the inequities in the medical establishment's treatment of women—a wakeup call that, she says, should be enough to fill us all with fury. “I’m not saying that of all the things that happen to women, lack of pain management is the worst of them,” she writes. ”But there are other methods of pain management for IUD insertions, and it’s time they’re taken seriously and offered more commonly.”
In a new essay for ELLE, Rowan writes about the challenges women face when fighting for pain relief for their IUD insertions and why, despite it all, she's still glad she got hers. Read the full story at the link in bio.

@marcnewsonofficial latest aluminum creation may not carry the auction-record prestige of his iconic Lockheed Lounge chair, but it brings the designer's signature innovation to travel. @louisvuitton is launching the Horizon Aluminum on June 12, marking the first-ever aluminum version of Newson's Horizon suitcase and the House's first aluminum luggage design.⁠
⁠
While its sleek, boxy silhouette appears deceptively simple, the suitcase completely rethinks aluminum luggage construction. Newson developed an ultra-thin frame system attached to a single-piece 3D-molded shell, eliminating both rivets and folded aluminum panels for a cleaner, more fluid design. The result is a suitcase that pairs Louis Vuitton craftsmanship with the kind of engineering precision expected from the former Apple designer behind it.

@blue_blue_official introduces a shirt crafted from the brand’s original yarn-dyed indigo linen twill, a custom-developed fabric that combines the texture of denim with the lightness of fine-count linen.⁠
⁠
Cut in a regular-fit silhouette with relaxed proportions, the buttonless skipper design delivers an effortless summer feel with a refined, easygoing look. Needless to say, it's made in Japan.

